  "event_preview": "Baku City Circuit measures 6.003 km (3.730 mi) and features 20 turns along the shores of the Caspian Sea and through the narrow streets of Baku's historic Old City, Azerbaijan — the fourth-longest circuit on the Formula 1 calendar. Built in 2016, the layout is a study in contrasts: after a flat-out 2.2 km blast down Neftchilar Avenue at over 340 km/h, drivers are suddenly compressed into a medieval stone labyrinth barely 7.6 metres wide with walls centimetres from the cockpit. The circuit runs counterclockwise and is infamous for its treacherous mix of high-speed walls, blind crests and violent braking zones that have produced some of the most chaotic and dramatic races in the modern era. Track evolution across the weekend is extreme — the street surface is virgin at the start of practice and rubbered in to an entirely different character by Sunday, making tyre management and session timing critical. The official race lap record stands at 1:43.009, set by Charles Leclerc for Ferrari during the 2019 Azerbaijan Grand Prix, while the all-time qualifying lap record belongs to Valtteri Bottas, who clocked a 1:40.495 for Mercedes in Q3 of that same weekend. Tyre supplier Pirelli brought the C4, C5, and C6 tyre compounds.",
